docs.text: zero effect gets its title from the main character , daryl zero ( bill pullman ) , although we don't understand what it truly means until the very last line of dialogue in the film .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: zero is a private investigator , perhaps the best private investigator who ever lived ( at least he'd like to think so ) .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: however , he's a socially inept being , and eccentric in every possible way -- this fact certainly makes his talents as a private eye even more bewildering than they already are .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: zero's accomplice is steve arlo ( ben stiller ) , a " normal " guy who does the business side of the job -- he's the one who actually speaks to clients and explains zero's greatness as an investigator .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the opening scene has steve explaining the many virtues of zero's talents to soon-to-be client gregory stark ( ryan o'neal ) .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: it turns out that stark has lost a key to a safe deposit box , and is now being blackmailed for something that he apparently knows nothing about .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: zero takes the case , and the plot thickens .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: his path leads to a young , pretty paramedic named gloria sullivan ( kim dickens ) .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: despite her luminous and seemingly-harmless presence , she turns out to be the one blackmailing stark .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: through his investigations , zero learns why , but not without developing feelings for gloria -- feelings that , because of his reclusive behavior , are new and confusing to him .

docs.text: i have no particular affinity towards the mystery genre of film .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i can idly enjoy movies about private investigators , and , every once in a while , a film like chinatown comes a long that blows me away ( actually , no private eye film has ever reached chinatown's greatness ) .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: zero effect , which is jake kasdan's first effort as writer/director , is a film about a private investigator that succeeds in all attempts : it's an original , funny , and completely involving motion picture .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: with so many cliches available to this genre , i find it amazing that kasdan avoided all of them .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: but he didn't just successfully avoid flaws : he has created a great film here , one that had me interested and fascinated from the first shot to the final moment .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: take , for starters , the great cast of characters .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: pullman is terrific as zero , showing a comic flair that i really haven't seen from him since spaceballs .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: zero is the kind of guy who seems at ease switching personalities so frequently as he does here ; the fact that he's an almost exaggeratedly twisted , emotionally unstable man outside of his profession is not at all difficult to believe .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: pullman's performance is much more layered than it might seem at first glance , and the occasional voice-over as he's going through the motions of his job are insightful and often hilarious .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: ben stiller is also a very funny individual ; he's the kind of comedian who makes normal lines sound funny .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: his character is also well-drawn , with an interesting subplot involving his girlfriend ( angela featherstone ) who is not happy with the extensive amounts of time he must spend away from her due to the unpredictability of his job .

docs.text: o'neal also gives his character a bit of depth ; and kim dickens , last seen ( and underused ) in mercury rising , gets a chance to show us her talent here , giving gloria the realism this kind of character really needs .

docs.text: i find zero effect to be an immensely funny and witty film .

docs.text: kasdan's humor is of the best kind -- soft spoken , and mostly dialogue-driven ( though there are some great visual jokes ) .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: it's the kind of humor that's funny even after you've seen it five or six times .

docs.text: there's one scene in which zero talks about how detached he is , an how that makes him such a great detective .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: what we see during this narration are various shots of him sitting on a bed , or standing motionlessly , with his hair destroyed and an utterly blank look painted on his unshaven face , his eyes pointing to something off camera , but obviously to nothing in particular .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i can't convey to you how funny this is , but what makes it great film making is that it has a point -- scenes like this are frequent , and they provide solid characterization of zero .

docs.text: as a side note , i don't consider myself an average viewer when it comes to comedy ( not to sound elitist ) -- i find things funny that many do not , and vice versa .

docs.text: i have a feeling the humor here won't appeal to everyone , but there's certainly enough story and character development to keep anyone's interest .
